## 1 Overview
In this lesson you will learn how to control a motor.

## 3 Components introduction

### L293D H-Bridge

Because the board isn't powerful enough alone to power a motor we are going to use a DC motor driver between the development board and the motor.

For this tutorial we use the **L293D H-Bridge Motor Driver**.

An **H-bridge** is an electronic circuit that enables a voltage to be applied across a load in opposite direction. These bridges are often used in robotics as they allow DC motors to run forwards or backwards.
This is an **open** H-Bridge schematic. The motor is not connected to any of the poles of the power supply, as all the four switches are open (S1, S2, S3, S4).

These are the two basic states of a H-Bridge. As you can see the voltage runs in opposite directions depending to what switches are closed.

We are going to represent shortly in a small table what each switch state does to the motor. **1** means that the switch is closed and **0** that the switch is open.

| S1 | S2 | S3 | S4 | Result            |
| -- | -- | -- | -- | ----------------- |
| 1  | 0  | 0  | 1  | Motor moves right |
| 0  | 1  | 1  | 0  | Motor moves left |
| 0  | 0  | 0  | 0  | Motor coasts |
| 0  | 1  | 0  | 0  | Motor coasts |
| 1  | 0  | 0  | 0  | Motor coasts |
| 0  | 0  | 1  | 0  | Motor coasts |
| 0  | 0  | 0  | 1  | Motor coasts |
| 0  | 0  | 1  | 1  | Motor brakes |
| 1  | 1  | 0  | 0  | Motor brakes |
| 0  | 1  | 0  | 1  | Short circuit |
| 1  | 0  | 1  | 0  | Short circuit |
| 0  | 1  | 1  | 1  | Short circuit |
| 1  | 0  | 1  | 1  | Short circuit |
| 1  | 1  | 0  | 1  | Short circuit |
| 1  | 1  | 1  | 0  | Short circuit |
| 1  | 1  | 1  | 1  | Short circuit |

The **L293D Motor Driver** has two voltage entrances to power the driver, and subsequently the motors. The **Vss** entrance is used to power the driver, and the **Vs** entrance to power the motors.

The pins we will control are **EN1, EN2, IN1, IN2, IN3, IN4. EN1 and EN2** are enable pins (we use them basically to start the motor). The **IN1, IN2** and respectively the **IN3, IN4** control the direction of the rotation.

## 5 Code

The code stars, as usual, by importing the libraries used, which are **time** and **RPi.GPIO**. Next, we will set the pin numbering as **GPIO.BOARD** and we will create three variables that will store the pins used by the motor driver and another two variables that will store the delay times for the motor to be On or Off.

In the next part of the code we will set the direction pins and the speed pin as **GPIO.OUT** and we will assign the speed pin to **GPIO.PWM** and the start the pwm instance. To optimize our code, we will create a function to stop the motor, that will be used further when we will play with the motor. In this function we have an instruction that will change the duty cycle to **0** and another two instructions to make the direction pins **GPIO.LOW**. Of course, we have added a sleep time before we can make another changes.

Before we begin talking about the infinite loop, we have to consider a problem that we came across in the previous lessons, which is that any line of code we have after the **while True** loop will not be executed after we force stop using **CTRL+C**, meant to interrupt the script from running, and our last instruction, which is **GPIO.cleanup()** to clean the used ports. To correct that, we will use exceptions. We will put our while loop inside a **try – pass** condition, and the loop will run until an exception will appear, which in our case is **KeyboardInterrupt** defined as **CTRL+C**. After we throw that exception, the code can safely end with success.

Now, back to the **while** loop where we will turn the motor on to 100% speed in one direction for 3 seconds, then turn it off for 1.5 seconds, and turn it back on to 100% speed in the opposite direction and then back off. We will do the same things also for the 50% speed.

"""
 * Credits: https://www.plusivo.com
 *
 * Lesson 5: Controlling a motor
 *
 * In this lesson, you will learn how to control a DC motor.
 *
 * Make sure you have connected the components correctly according
 * to the guide.
 *
 * More information about the connection can be found in the guide.
 *
 """
#we will import the sleep module from the time library
from time import sleep
#we will import the RPi.GPIO library with the name of GPIO
import RPi.GPIO as GPIO

#we will set the pin numbering to the GPIO.BOARD numbering
#for more details check the guide attached to this code
GPIO.setmode(GPIO.BOARD)

#the next variable stores the pin used to control the speed of the motor
motorspeed_pin = 8

#the next two variables store the pins used to control the direction of the motor
DIRA = 10
DIRB = 22

#the variable "delayOn" stores the time (in seconds) for the motor to remain On
delayOn = 3

#the variable "delayOff" stores the time (in seconds) for the motor to remain Off
delayOff = 1.5
#we will set the pins as output
GPIO.setup(motorspeed_pin, GPIO.OUT)
GPIO.setup(DIRA, GPIO.OUT)
GPIO.setup(DIRB, GPIO.OUT)

#the motorspeed_pin will be used as an enable pin on the motor driver
pwmPIN = GPIO.PWM(motorspeed_pin, 100)

#we start the pwm instance with a duty cycle of 0
pwmPIN.start(0)

#define a function to stop the motor
def turnOff():
        #this instruction is used to set the speed of the motor to 0 (Off)
        pwmPIN.ChangeDutyCycle(0)
        #in these instructions the state is irrelevant because the speed is 0
        GPIO.output(DIRA, GPIO.LOW)
        GPIO.output(DIRB, GPIO.LOW)
        sleep(delayOff)

try:
        while True:
                #this instruction is used to set the maximum speed of the motor
                pwmPIN.ChangeDutyCycle(100)
                #these instructions are used to turn on the motor in one direction
                GPIO.output(DIRA, GPIO.HIGH)
                GPIO.output(DIRB, GPIO.LOW)
                sleep(delayOn)

                #turn off the motor
                turnOff()

                #this instruction is used to set the maximum speed of the motor
                pwmPIN.ChangeDutyCycle(100)
                #these instructions are used to turn on the motor in the opposite direction
                GPIO.output(DIRA, GPIO.LOW)
                GPIO.output(DIRB, GPIO.HIGH)
                sleep(delayOn)

                #turn off the motor
                turnOff()

                #this instruction sets the motor speed to about 50%
                pwmPIN.ChangeDutyCycle(50)
                #these instructions are used to turn on the motor in one direction
                GPIO.output(DIRA, GPIO.HIGH)
                GPIO.output(DIRB, GPIO.LOW)
                sleep(delayOn)

                #turn off the motor
                turnOff()

                #this instruction sets the motor speed to about 50%
                pwmPIN.ChangeDutyCycle(50)
                #these instructions are used to turn on the motor in the opposite direction
                GPIO.output(DIRA, GPIO.LOW)
                GPIO.output(DIRB, GPIO.HIGH)
                sleep(delayOn)

                #turn off the motor
                turnOff()

except KeyboardInterrupt:
        pass

#clean all the used ports
GPIO.cleanup()
